1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,799
When you encounter a situation involving accessibility, what do you actually do?

2
00:00:04,799 --> 00:00:08,399
That is where the Accessibility Decision Path comes in.

3
00:00:08,399 --> 00:00:12,799
This is a five-step framework you can use in any moment.

4
00:00:12,799 --> 00:00:14,399
Step one is Pause.

5
00:00:14,399 --> 00:00:18,799
Before you act, take a breath and notice what is happening.

6
00:00:18,799 --> 00:00:20,399
Are you making assumptions?

7
00:00:20,399 --> 00:00:23,599
Is there a barrier you had not considered?

8
00:00:23,599 --> 00:00:25,199
Step two is Listen.

9
00:00:25,199 --> 00:00:28,000
Hear the person in front of you.

10
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:31,199
Ask how they would like to be supported.

11
00:00:31,199 --> 00:00:34,399
Do not assume you know what someone needs.

12
00:00:34,399 --> 00:00:36,000
Step three is Apply.

13
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:43,600
Use what you have learned — from this series, from your training, from your experience — to respond appropriately.

14
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:45,200
Step four is Adapt.

15
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:48,400
If your first approach does not work, adjust.

16
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:51,200
Flexibility is not a sign of failure.

17
00:00:51,200 --> 00:00:53,600
It is a sign of competence.

18
00:00:53,600 --> 00:00:56,000
And step five is Seek Support.

19
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:58,799
If you are unsure, ask for help.

20
00:00:58,799 --> 00:01:04,799
Contact your manager, reach out to Patient Relations, or consult with accessibility resources at UHN.

21
00:01:04,799 --> 00:01:08,399
You do not have to have all the answers.

22
00:01:08,399 --> 00:01:15,199
These five steps — Pause, Listen, Apply, Adapt, Seek Support — will come back in every guide.

23
00:01:15,199 --> 00:01:16,799
They are your anchor.
